Author: Audo#5667
Content:
Hey guys, I'm looking for ideas. Let's think big for a moment... how do we *really* make Komodo succeed? In my mind we just must focus on building a large ecosystem. Here's what I am thinking: 

Our vision is to build an ecosystem.

To do that we need to empower developers and start-ups to build products using our technology. Thus we must understand what they need and then have all the solutions ready for them.

Here‚Äôs a list of what a developer or start-up might be looking for:

- get a high-level overview of what Komodo is about
- understand what he can build with the technology
- browse actual projects which use our technology
- access Komodo‚Äôs developer documentation & code examples
- learn more about blockchain & coding in general (courses)
- participate in networking opportunities: a forum to talk with other developers
- get capital for development
- have a platform to let the community know about the project he started
- provide updates about his progress
- share his experiences & frustrations through a blog & articles

Question  1: What is a developer or project looking for? What do they need?
Question 2: How do we build a scalable platform (not in a technical sense) that empowers the developer?

Author: Audo#5667
Content: what are all the components we need for this dragon to wake up? We have been discussing about launching a community news/blogging platform, and we have also been thinking how to use/leverage our forum more... how do we empower and activate the community members.

Author: yorklab#7270
Content: GUI, GUI, GUI.  Komodo is so diverse and goes through so many changes that creating a single GUI  for the entire exco system  will take some time. I think @grewalsatinder  library and education approach to attract new devs is a great idea, but that also will take time. In the meantime perhaps the team can come up with something that is very narrow in scope; start off with something basic. It doesn't matter what it is, as long as it's a GUI that performs a task that the rest of the crypto world says "Well, the best way to do that is with Komodo's (whatever the app is).  For instance: in parallel with the MM 2.O development someone also develop's a very basic BarterDEX GUI that can only trade BTC-KMD and KMD-BTC and nothing more to start with. If it's really easy to use it could create a lot of demand and of course more attention to Komodo. After writing this I realize this may not answer your specific questions, but it's something I've been thinking about.....A simple GUI that performs a simple task that people will use.

Author: Regnar#6164
Content:
also @Audo I like this idea by Clovyr which has a smooth button focused way of building basic chains.
<https://clovyr.io/>
Which I imagine would have simple things like uploading an image, choose a name, and sliding bar for parameters of coin amount and premine. buttons to choose distribution method (dICO, ICO, AirDrop, mining) if you want mining halvings, and how long you want the chain to grow for (say 20 years, and it will auto calculate the block size needed). Tx fees, if you want a founders fee on transactions, privacy functions (zk snarks, starks, ring CT), choose mining algorithm (equihash, verushash, Proof of stake, others, or hybrid with a percent slider. A single click for dPoW protection, auto push updates (KMD updates are auto pushed to your chain), and selecting where you want to start your nodes/mining (have click options for various servers like AWS, other 3rd parties, or local machine), if you want Agama and BarterDEX integration, and whatever else will be modular. 

Then at the end it spits out a summary document showing all the relevant chain related highlights so other people can truly see what your chain is, as well as a hash of the chain document information and date of time, that we notarize to the KMD main chain channel to prove a chain exists in our ecosystem (just for the coolness and legitimacy sake, so someone can see a chain information and KNOW that there was a premine or w.e.)

And of course any of the additional services that actually cost money will need to be paid.

Author: Regnar#6164
Content: oh, an autoscale button! you add the option for autoscale, and anytime your chain starts to hit peak load it spawns up the scaling chain either locally, on AWS, or whatever else.

Author: Regnar#6164
Content: @Audo I noticed that on the interim page we seem to have dropped off Privacy and Simplicity from the 5 pillars and replaced it with Adaptability. Was this intentional?

Author: Audo#5667
Content: @Lennart yes that's important for sure. We need to tell our story how we differ from the general purpose blockchain platforms (which a single chain / shared infrastructure) and the block producer platforms  such as EOS. Doing that so that everyone understand what we talk about is a challange for sure, but one of the goals of the rebrand.

Author: Audo#5667
Content:
@Regnar yes, we used to have 5 technology pillars, but we changed them to be 4 technology pillars + 4 business pillars. Thus the privacy was dropt from the technology pillars.

Privacy is important pillar, so I would personally still consider adding it and having 5 technology pillars and 5 business pillars. What do you guys think?

Author: Audo#5667
Content:
Simplicity was moved to the business pillars, which are:
 - Autonomy
 - Flexibility
 - Simplicity
 - Reliability

Author: Audo#5667
Content:
We always felt the first three technology pillars were very strong: security, scalability, interoperability.

I like the new 'adaptability' pillar a lot as it covers Komodo's key strength, which is that each blockchain can be fully customized, even their consensus rules can be changed to develop powerful "smart contracts". In other words, we can say that with Komodo you can *launch special purpose blockchains versus getting fixed features on a general purpose blockchain platform*.

Author: Fartmasta#7840
Content: I don't think the website needs much more or anything. When was the last time you went to Microsoft.com and gave an f what it looks like. If KMD is good, it's good enough to move up in this space. Right now it's a popularity contest. The projects can shift ranks at a drop of a hat. Komodo's tech is a great building, increasing blockchain and btc's foundation. The work can be seen as creative, robust, innovative and flat out cool as hell. Other projects focus a huge amount of time on partnerships, business, legalities, economics, and image. Resources get overdone, and freedom to create is hindered. Tensions build in a tight-fitted federation leaving the dev's tired and pressured. Komodo's move towards rebranding is a refreshment of personality. It gives more presence. It will attract those who have given into the hype and not artistry. There are two visions: one many use to make something likable, and the other few use to like something they make. Ok that was too long lol.
